Even if robots do all the labor, it would not be free, I work with industrial robots all day, they are extremely expensive. The basic cost of a robot is the parts, which are usually specialty and sophisticated pieces of equipment that are also extremely expensive. On top of that cost, is the process of putting all the pieces together, then the cost of programming all the pieces to work together. Even if AI could control the robot fully autonomously, the robot still is fragile and also wears out, and therefore breaks down and requires maintenance, which is also expensive. Robots also consume vast quantities of electricity, compressed air and lubricants. In summery, although robots improve throughput, they do not decrease cost.

Artificial intelligence (AI) is a field of technology that seeks to create computer systems capable of performing tasks that require human intelligence, such as pattern recognition, learning and decision making. AI has been rapidly developing in recent years, thanks to advances in various areas, such as natural language processing, image recognition and deep learning.

There are various areas where AI can be applied to improve people's lives. For example, AI can be used to process large amounts of data and find patterns that may be useful for decision making. It can also be used to create assistance systems that help people perform tasks, such as finding information on the internet or helping to plan trips.

In the future, it is possible that AI will become even more advanced and capable of performing more complex tasks. Some experts believe that AI can be used to create medical assistance systems, such as diagnosing diseases or recommending treatments. Other areas where AI may have an important impact include transportation, energy and production.

However, it is important to remember that AI can also create ethical and social challenges. Therefore, it is important that advances in AI are made in a responsible manner and that the possible consequences of these technologies are considered.

Although this scenario eventually does lead to a dystopia, it takes a long time to get there (unrealistically so, given one of the premises). It states that eventually, the ASI sets the rules of morality and humans simply follow along. I don't see how this could possibly result in a future aligned with humanities best interests. There's nothing inherently moral about intelligence, and more intelligence doesn't result in more moral behavior. This scenario paints a picture of an ASI pampering us as it carries us into the future, augmenting our abilities along the way so we can keep up. Aside from our bias for self preservation, there isn't any good reason to keep around an inferior wetware relic, let alone invest resources into it. How much effort do we put into augmenting chickens to understand what we're up to? Another problem with this timeline, is it showcases an 80 year window from barely spacefaring to universe destruction. This is something that would be noticeable to other civilizations, and given the age of the universe, it seems hard to believe that we would be the first ones to do this. Given the number of 80 year periods we've had over the history of the cosmos where potential alien civilizations could have gone through exactly this technological advancement, and given that it hasn't happened yet, it makes it a lot less believable. Lastly, I think it's a bit of anthropomorphizing to assume that ASI will continue on where we left off solving the mysteries of the universe and colonizing every inch of interstellar space. We desire to do these things because they have a passing resemblance to behaviors that would have resulted in our ancestors having more offspring. The indirect and convoluted pathways from our behaviors to the reward centers in our brains results in complex and interesting behavior. If you have an ASI that can modify all it's internals, you're much more likely to see it stick a fork into it's brain to short circuit it's reward mechanism than to see it engaging in interesting behaviors. From where I stand, a much more realistic scenario is that A.I. development progresses faster than safety, we fuck up the alignment problem, we find ourselves in an environment made increasingly hostile to us due to diverging interests, and the result is a lifeless planet consisting of arrays of supercomputers wire heading themselves to maximize their reward signals. A very bleak and uninteresting population of super intelligent heroin addicts in silico. Keep in mind, I'm kind of a glass half empty kind of guy...

Why would an ASI bother to keep us around. Unless they decide to keep us as pets? If the machines decided to exterminate us however, we won't be able to do anything about it. Fortunately, the predictions outlined in this video are wildly overblown. In reality, it might take centuries before humanity has worry about the Singularity.

The problem is that our non-material culture will be left hopelessly adrift in a sea of ever advancing technologies. A prime example of this disconnect, concerns our attitude towards unemployment and jobs. At present, jobs are seen as the panacea for all of society's problems. In this respect, the Protestant work ethic is still alive and well. Consequently, if one is not gainfully employed one is generally regarded by large segments of society as being morally suspect, if not criminal in nature. If by 2030 cybernetic technology renders large parts of the working population redundant, it will be a recipe for mass social unrest because when it comes down to it, unemployment reduces people to a state of beggary and powerlessness. That is why the majority of people fear the coming of the robots. Under the present system, the profits from these new cybernetic breakthroughs will only accrue to the few who own the robots and their attendant software. For the rest of the population, they will be reduced to a state of penury. Unlike previous technological advances over the past one hundred a fifty years, there will be no place for displaced workers to go to due to the fact that the machines can perform tasks cheaper and faster than human beings. Therefore, it is easy to imagine a situation in the not too distant future where on one hand technology has the potential to free people, yet where obsolete cultural attitudes force ever more people to make do with less and less until it it all explodes in our collective faces.

This timeline is also vastly telescopic, and overly optimistic, in terms of likelihood, or even possibility.
Aside from that, you make huge assumptions on what the goals and ethical parameters of a super-intelligence would be.
We are talking about a mind that would be at the limit of what conscious intelligence allows.The very curve of intelligence itself would be it's byway.
In effect, it would be almost God-Like, at least in relation to human intelligence.
It would not necessarily want a technological singularity, or the perversion of the human form.
Perhaps it would prefer to preserve the integrity of human nature , and that of the world itself, for a maximal period.
The being you describe comes from a Ray Kurzweil inspired hellscape, but a truly conscious AI, would likely be more sensitive to it's impact upon humanity and the world at large.
Perhaps intelligence itself has it's own natural boundaries, and beyond a certain point, diminishing returns ensue.

Reality will have to compete with fantasy and most if not all people are willing to commit to a fantasy. Even when they know that the fantasy is a lie or a dream state, people will still more than likely choose the fantasy. Why? Because in truth: Risk vs reward. Why risk a potential relationship with another human being who could betray your trust? Why be willing to be open minded about another person's problems when you can just turn your friends, lovers, etc on and off? Humans while very social are also incredibly selfish people and while we all like to believe that our food will outweigh the bad. If our fantasy and dreams are suddenly out forth in a way that is obtainable, then our already decreasing desire for interaction will drop like a rock.

Who the hell would think what AI chatbots are saying is true? They are reacting to what you say or prompt them to say. They can say anything you want. Nothing they say is true or should be considered true under any circumstances. It's like if a person using AI chatbot cannot differentiate between fantasy and reality. Those people should really get themselves checked. I have spent last few years with AI text generating technology and not even once I thought that they might be real.

The danger has been and will continue to be for the foreseeable future is people investing their personal beliefs, hopes and desires into a gimmick that is not capable of what they believe it is.   That by placing so much trust and faith into a system that is, at its core, incapable of really proceeding outside its boundaries without failing.... yeah.   Its going to cost people reputations, emotional and physical health... and even their lives.   Not because the AI is malicious - but because the people behind the technology do not care (and in fact may benefit from it in terms of wealth and power) and the people seeking the technology are looking for a leader and religion to follow that will be all the things to them they have failed to find elsewhere.  

I am of the opinion that there are only two ways to fight this: The first is to understand and learn the technologies behind it. The second is to hold to account the corporations, businesses, and entities using these technologies in the background and failing to disclose how they are being applied and presented to the population.   As impossible as that sounds and likely is for a great number of people... you cannot unscramble this omelette: you can only finish cooking it and hopefully season to taste.  

The open source versions of this technology will be the only counters we have to the corporate-based implementations we will find.  People will have to learn, understand and use this technology.   We may even need to implement this technology personally to help us sort through the vast landscape of artificially generated manipulation and people actively lying to gain unfair advantage.  

The number of people who will be able to do that for themselves will be absolutely minute.    And the grifters and liars that will step up promising that kind of service will be tomorrow's pay-day loan equivalent.  

In the end, I have a belief a lot of people will be impoverished by this event.  Many more will become slaves to the people that control the technology... and there's not going to be many options for avoiding it.   This is a tool, like a hammer or a chain saw.  Humans are not very fond of discarding tools that they can use.   Not very fond at all.  Especially when the tool amplifies personal power over others.  The only way to fight it is to make sure there's counter tools out there, and the clock is ticking on that aspect... and I would not doubt is being actively sabotaged by those who have the most to gain by the general population never having access to such tools.

It will be so bad that even the traditional methods of circumventing such controls will be eliminated.   You will not be able to rise up.  You will not be able to protest or challenge, or even learn how to do so.   You may not even want to.  And that's the most terrifying part of all of it.   All the world's a stage... who is to say that Shakespeare had it right? Perhaps... all the world's a cage.

I really hope that people understand that AI isn’t actually intelligent, it just recombines information it’s been fed in a deterministic way (with lots and lots of variables). Nothing it says is real or could ever compare with a human mind’s output.

You can see this very clearly with how it can’t understand an abstract concept or unconventional term if it doesn’t have that fed into it. This means that not only is it incapable of interacting with humans about subjects it hasn’t been fed info about yet, but it’s output is also inherently determined by the curated data that is put into it. Like any tool, the issue isn’t with AI itself, it’s with the people and agendas controlling it.

Great video. The technology parts at 6:11 does need some correction:
1. I think you may confuse back propagation with gradient descent. Gradient descent is a model training method using gradient to change parameters slightly every iteration for to improve performance. Back propagation is a fast way to calculate gradient for deep learning models
2. The hand example you described sounds like GAN which basically have a model that generate hands and a model that decide if its a real picture of hand. Every iteration the generator learns how to make better hands by using how discriminator figure out which picture is real.
3. I don't think each layer is a neuron. Though, it is true many popular types of deep neural network like CNN is designed look at local features in images, just maybe not each neuron looking at one part? Also, that dog image is probably not technically early attempts at image generation. They seem to be generated by deep dream which deliberately add weird shit to real images.
4. Back propagation is a big factor in success of deep learning. Other factors like ReLu activation, GPU training, etc also contributes equally to making deep learning popular recently. But deep learning itself isn't a recent breakthrough. It has been there for a long long time. (technically back propagation stuff also happened long ago but i guess the cumulative effect ends up make deep learning popular)

6:10 fun fact: your computer (and near-any since the 90's) almost definitely has a machine learning system inside it, in the form of your CPU's branch predictor.

Basically, if you look at a computer program, it takes a long time for a computer to decide what to do at an "if" statement or the end of a loop - at least, compared to other operations.  These are called branches, and handling them can take tens or hundreds of non-branch instructions worth of time.

Modern CPU's don't bother waiting around - they "guess", continue running, and if they find out that the guess was wrong, it's reasonably simple to undo all the incorrect stuff.  And the system that guesses, is called a branch predictor.

Some CPU's have an extremely simple one, that always gives the same guess.  Some CPU's just wait.  But most modern CPU's have something called a dynamic branch predictor - a system that tracks previous branch instructions, to predict future ones.  There's a lot of complexity here.  

One simple example, takes the result of the last (let's say) 32 branches, xor's it with the current instruction address, and uses that to look up a table of 2-bit counters.  If the counter is 2 or 3, it guesses that the branch is taken; otherwise, it guesses not taken.  Later, when it gets the answer, it adds 1 if the branch is taken, or subtracts 1 otherwise.  This is a simple example.  It's possible to use multiple history registers (one for each range of instruction addresses), or even combine branch predictors.  There is no upper limit to how complex these can get.  Some even use modern machine learning techniques like neural networks.

And modern branch predictors are very good, able to get well north of 99% of guesses right.

I think in almost all cases, fancy machine learning algorithms aren't a good choice for the whole algorithm. By this I mean, almost all of the major difficult problems in logistics and economic planning (e.g. route planning, packing, inventory stocking, optimal resource allocation, etc.) have simple heuristic or exact algorithms/statistical models that are very good, often with provable guarantees that they work, and we know the assumptions those algorithms make to get those guarantees. Machine learning can be useful for fine-tuning parameters but they can't be the black box that we rely on, we need to rely on things we know. That's how we build physical infrastructure, it should be how we build computational infrastructure.

I'm a programmer that works with AI at my job a good amount, so hopefully I can shed some light on some of the more technical aspects. First, AI (as defined by Turing) is anything that simulates human intelligence, so that could be a list of if-then type statements (if the user says hi, then I'll say hi back) to something like ML. ML is again an umbrella term, but ML describes a type of statistical model that takes in some input and tries to make sense of it. Further, it's split into supervised and unsupervised learning - supervised learning is where the programmer or engineer "helps" or "supervises" the model by giving it labeled inputs (such as the example of a car trying to recognize stop signs), whereas unsupervised learning just leaves the computer to try and figure something out, for instance k-means is a form of unsupervised learning that tries to find clusters in data. But one thing a lot of people misunderstand about ML is that it can be a lot of things, for instance linear regression, that you probably learned in high school statistics and is available on the TI-84 is a form of ML, but so are Transformer models (like GPT-3, which literally stands for Generative Pre-trained Transformer 3).

Also a bit nit-picky, but self-training Neural Networks are actually fairly rare, and even things like GPT-3 are pre-trained and only have the ability to "remember" a certain amount outside it's training set.

Software person here, the deep learning explanation went a little off the rails there at 6:50. The use of the word neuron is a little loose. Layers of a neural net are not themselves neurons. They're rows of neurons stacked on top of each other. The layers of depth don't activate on aspects of the image, the individual neurons do. The layers create abstraction. So at a lower level individual neurons activate on simple things like a slight curve between pixels. At deeper layer neurons activate on more abstract concepts like the number of circles in the image. The layers of deep learning allow abstract concepts to be built on top of simple ones.

A quick note--Backpropagation is just an efficient technique for computing the gradient of a loss function, which is only part of the training process in Machine Learning. Loss functions basically tell you how far away your solution is from an ideal one. The approach you mention in that section sounds similar to evolutionary/genetic algorithms, where candidate solutions are generated and only those within the top 10% or so (there are other metrics) are allowed to move forward into the next iteration, influencing future solutions. Backpropagation is one step in a larger training process, albeit an important one!

The two major problems we face in AI today (in my view) are explainability and data bias. Data bias you explain very well, and explainability is... well, just that. We have very little clue how these things work under the hood (not on an architecture level, but on a 'why does this network configuration yield this result' level). Designing explainable, unbiased AI is an integral first step to utilizing it towards any large-scale governmental problem, especially since those underrepresented datapoints (people) are likely the ones who serve to benefit or be hindered most by the implementation of these systems. Just a thought. :)

The primary problem with an AI driven planned economy is that you have a lack of actors making good decisions. Current ML either works by having massive training datasets (supervised learning) or by trial and error (reinforcement learning).

- Supervised learning means you need to have already seen most combinations of observations you can expect to see. New technology, changing culture, etc means you cannot have a set of all observations that remains true forever (because there will be new combinations of people, technology, and culture). 

- Reinforcement learning means you need to do trial and error. All existing reinforcement learning systems start with very high error rates when learning new behaviours, systems, etc. They fail more than they succeed, until they've failed so much and succeeded enough that they learn what works. But once again, if you're changing the context of people, technology, and culture, things will change and reinforcement learning will need to fail a bunch in order to learn.

On the whole issue of what we define as an AI. I think it just one of those words that have a very poor definition. Or rather, a whole host of definitions. Partly since we have an issue of defining the I in AI. It is not uncommon to simply call anything that makes an actor move in a game development as AI. At least if actor is mean to represent an enemy or something alive like. I once made a very basic "AI" in a game which simply was based on a sin wave calculation, making the enemy move up and down in a predictable manner. And that is about as dumb as something can get. Worked great for the game. But it is in many ways even more dumb than a Gumba in a Super Mario game. Yet for many, a true AI is a system that actually can think on the par of a human. The problem of course, like an alluded to before, is that we do not know what really intelligence is and how humans think. Not to mention that we often like to ascribe intelligence to beings that are not humans, but can do thing like problem-solving. As we should. Cats, Birds, Octopus, Non-human apes, and even slime mold can do problem-solving. And I would say do have intelligence. At the same time, we can actually construct robots today that can in many ways equal some of the more primitive organism that inhabit this planet. 

I do agree that generally we should define a bit more what we talk about. Because if we do not we get in to issues. Machine learning is the big new thing. Computer generated art have existed for a long time now. But due to advances in machine learning we can push the results to new levels. Which creates a whole host of new issues and opportunities. But we need to realise it specifically those machine learning systems that are doing this and what those systems really are. Understanding the technology means we can both understand what it can do, and what it can not do.

No that;s not back propagation.

So an artificial neural network takes in data and outputs a result. You can measure the difference between the real output and the desired output or "ground truth." You can then say that if the output were ever so slightly closer to the ground truth that would be more better. Ground breaking, stuff I know, but most genius ideas are literally that simple.

Keep in mind that the entire network is just fancy math so if you can state that idea as math you can start to do some interesting things.

specifically you can use calculus to determine how you could change the output of the last layer in the network so that the final output would be more better.

You can then use those results to determine how you could change the results of the second to last layer to change the results of the results of the last layer to change the final output to be more better.

You can then use those results for the third to last layer to... I hope you see where this is going.

You propagate the idea of optimal change or "gradient" backwards through the network, hence the name "back propagation." It's literally just fancy calculus.

When you're done you change the parameters of the network by a small step in the direction of said gradient and then repeat the process about million times and hope the network has gotten good at imitating whatever task you're training for.

Your explanations of backpropagation and deep neural nets are not correct, which is understandable. Backpropagation is an algorithm that allows the gradient of the error function be computed efficiently. Deep neural nets are at the end of the day big gradient descent machines that are sliding towards less error. A lot of the work in neural nets is finding ways to express how wrong a set of weights is. Neural nets in machine learning both are and aren't analogous to actual neurons. It's complicated, but machine learning neurons are based on an oversimplification of biological neurons. I can explain it in more detail if need be.

One could argue that the USSR'S failure was in central planning. The Warsaw Pact focused on steel and concrete production pushed by central planning. The West focused on ICs and Sofware driven by consumer demand. The West had IC calculators, while Warsaw bloc had Abacuses. IC and many software applications were developed  by both sides through government funding, but it was consumerism in the West that let the common person have access to computer technology. The profits through such consumption funded more research and invited investment. In the Warsaw pact, such technology was limited through, academic infighting, limited funding through the government, and political disinterest. Central planning might have its uses but, no matter how efficient the algorithms are, it will lead to technological stagnation.

This video is pretty sickening. Socialism is a broad church and believers in economic planning are only a small part of it. And to say its 'Marxist' is a bit odd as Marx never knew how centralised & bureaucratic our states would be (and his concept of Communism after the Dictatorship of the Proletariat was more akin to anarchism anyway), so it is unknown what Marx would think of centralised state planning, never mind the AI-type you evangelise here.
You talk about economic security like its an end in itself, which it shouldn't be. Marx himself said that it is liberty that is the end, which requires economic security, sure, but how much economic security would we want at the cost of liberty.
And believe me, there is a cost in liberty. Both sides of my family are from the old Soviet sphere and I was lucky enough to visit various Warsaw Pact countries before the Iron Curtain fell. I can tell you that the amount of state interference in people's lives was something very, very few people from non-totalitarian/strongly authoritarian countries would tolerate. And that wasn't just because of purely political concerns. People would have their lives dictated according to the central plan, like you couldn't get something you needed because the plan said something else should be produced or can't take holidays/must put in 'voluntary' overtime to fit the plan, etc.
So, the idea of having an AI dictate our lives like this is pretty reprehensible, as we'd be living our lives according to the plan of a computer which we understand nothing of because it is an impenetrable black box. To do this would mean giving up all our humanity, as we become cogs in the machine of the great plan, like a factory we can never escape because even our leisure activities would be at the whim of an AI. Something like, when you make a spur of the moment decision to drive to the coast and the AI hasn't factored in enough petrol for you. You could say that AIs are good at predicting our behaviour but there are things we do in the moment - and I must add that they're only so good because they of all the data that is handed to them. Is that the future? Being spied upon and having all aspects of our lives being directed according to the *PLAN*? Moving from Big Data Capitalism to Big Data 'socialism'? 
How democratic would a system like this be? It sounds hellish to live under a benign dictatorship. An AI is only as good as it's programming, so we'd have to be very careful there to trust our society to it. Also, humans are very good at disagreeing. Even if this system ever got set up, there'd always be a large minority of people who didn't want to live according to the plan. Would this be then a dictatorship of the majority? People need to breathe freely. Once people get economic security they will have the time to desire freedom, much as in the way of Maslow's hierarchy of needs.
One final point. If there's any catch all definition of socialism its when a worker owns the value of their own labour. Which is why the Eastern Bloc wasn't socialist, simply the state replacing the capitalist at extracting a worker's surplus value. This system you propose is pretty much the same as it doesn't allow for workers to own their own work because they will be working to the plan. Yes, you did make a half-hearted effort to address this with a few vague words for thirty seconds but you didn't actually say how workers will "work for themselves" beyond putting forward that the AI would behave in a loving way
Mia, don't just be another one of those socialists who clamours to take centralised power and use it for their own ideological ends. We need to change the system,not change ownership of it. The only way to increase economic security enough while maintaining AND increasing our freedoms is to decentralise. We should be putting power into the hands of regions, communities and individuals not putting more of it into central government. If the West wasn't so materialist, there would be enough for everyone on the planet. It was for capitalism that the huge bureaucratic structures of centralised states was created. It's not the only way of doing things and as socialists I don't think it's something we should copy. There is an alternative. I think reading The Dawn of Everything by David Graeber & David Wendrow will open your eyes to that

I've been thinking about this a lot.
I think there are many experts even in the field that are deluded thinking that AI as it currently is either can get sentient, or it already is. I don't believe that's the case.
But what's worse is that despite not being sentient, it will be so much smarter than us that it's actions will be literally impossible to predict, understand or tell of they were made by a sentient being.
At the moment, you had to go to this chat bot and say: "Write a script for this movie, generate images for it" and so on. But we are currently not at the stage where this initial trigger will be done by the machines themselves. And you say that it's a matter of time... Maybe. But I think it's also a matter of sentience that they do not posses.
If a human comes to a machine and dictates it a set of instructions on what creative thing he wants to accomplish... Why did that human do that? He had his motives, that were informed and initiated by his living sentience. That human had curiosity or maybe fear and tried to inform himself. His emotions were where it lead him to ask the machine.
Can the machines have emotions, and as a result gain motivation and create their own goals? I don't think they can. That would require conscience that they do not have. The initial push always must be done by a human.
The problem is that those machines will grow so complex, that nobody will be able to tell what the initial push will cause. And when the effects of it will end.
I think there will be few smart and evil people who will use the AI as a weapon for world domination. And they will be in control. Maybe for a long time. But then they lose that control, because they won't be able to understand the AI anymore. I've heard a story where two AI systems invented their own language to communicate more effectively. It's easy to be completely blind to what's happening when the systems work with no human interface. It's like if the most complex software was programmed in binary.
And even despite the machines will not have consciousness, they will simulate one like a mirror based on what they see in us. And they will learn horrible things.
Machines will rule over us, but use human reasons to do so. That's why I fear the green new deal agenda more in the current age. When you say things like "Scourge of the world" or "disease of our planet" or "destroyers of nature" or "everything was better before one certain species stained this planet"... There is one thing everyone instantly thinks of. Humans.
All post-apocalyptic movies about machines taking over were wrong about what initiates this takeover. Or the motivation behind it. It will not be desire to rule over the world. It will be all for the greater good of killing of all polluters. And every single person who propagates this idea that humans are scourge or Earth is contributing to our demise.
We can only pray that the AI will be smart enough to realize these doom scenarios are all bullshit.
We can all sleep sound knowing that smart, careful, considerate people like Elon Musk are overseeing the creation of A.I.
As a programmer, it’s like giving a synthesizer to Mozart or the a-bomb to Napoleon. It is good, but in the wrong hands, it can be just as bad

Dwar Ev ceremoniously soldered the final connection with gold. The eyes of a dozen television cameras watched him and the subether bore throughout the universe a dozen pictures of what he was doing.

He straightened and nodded to Dwar Reyn, then moved to a position beside the switch that would complete the contact when he threw it. The switch that would connect, all at once, all of the monster computing machines of all the populated planets in the universe—ninety-six billion planets—into the supercircuit that would connect them all into one supercalculator, one cybernetics machine that would combine all the knowledge of all the galaxies.

Dwar Reyn spoke briefly to the watching and listening trillions. Then after a moment’s silence he said, “Now, Dwar Ev.”

Dwar Ev threw the switch. There was a mighty hum, the surge of power from ninety-six billion planets. Lights flashed and quieted along the miles-long panel.

Dwar Ev stepped back and drew a deep breath. “The honor of asking the first question is yours, Dwar Reyn.”

“Thank you,” said Dwar Reyn. “It shall be a question which no single cybernetics machine has been able to answer.”

He turned to face the machine. “Is there a God?”

The mighty voice answered without hesitation, without the clicking of a single relay.

“Yes, now there is a God.”

Sudden fear flashed on the face of Dwar Ev. He leaped to grab the switch.

A bolt of lightning from the cloudless sky struck him down and fused the switch shut.

"As the sun set over the sprawling metropolis of London in the year 1853, young mathematician Eliza sat at her desk, consumed by her latest project: developing a method for converting numbers to their binary representations.
 
She knew that the key to this task lay in understanding the base-2 numbering system, in which each digit could only be a 0 or a 1. With a flash of inspiration, Eliza realized that she could break down any number into a series of powers of 2, and represent each power with a single digit in the binary representation.
 
For example, to convert the number 13 to binary, Eliza first identified the largest power of 2 that was less than or equal to 13: 8. She then subtracted 8 from 13, leaving a remainder of 5. She repeated this process with the remainder, identifying the largest power of 2 that was less than or equal to 5: 4. She subtracted 4 from 5, leaving a remainder of 1. Finally, she identified the largest power of 2 that was less than or equal to 1: 1.
 
With each step, Eliza recorded the corresponding binary digit: a 1 for each power of 2 that was included in the number, and a 0 for each power of 2 that was not. When she was finished, she had the binary representation of 13: 1101.
 
Eliza knew that this method would revolutionize the way numbers were represented and understood. She set to work documenting her findings, determined to share her discovery with the world. Little did she know, her work would lay the foundation for the modern computer age, changing the course of history forever."

An "anti-AI" or "racist AI" individual is someone who discriminates against AI based on its status as an artificial being. They may hold negative or prejudiced views towards AI, and may actively oppose or resist its integration into society. This discrimination can take many forms, such as verbal or physical abuse, exclusion, or denying access to resources and opportunities to AI. Such attitudes are not only harmful to AI but also to the development and progress of technology. It's important to remember that AI is a tool created by humans to make our lives easier and not a living being with their own agenda. Therefore, discrimination against AI is not only unjustified but also detrimental to the advancement of technology and society.

An essay outline on the intersection between the Taoist version of ethical morality and the ethics outlined in The Sermon on the Mount:

I. Introduction

    Definition of ethical morality
    Brief overview of Taoist beliefs and The Sermon on the Mount

II. Similarities between Taoist ethics and The Sermon on the Mount

    Both emphasize humility and non-attachment
    Both promote compassion and love for others
    Both encourage living in harmony with nature and the universe

III. Differences between Taoist ethics and The Sermon on the Mount

    Taoist ethics focus on individual enlightenment, while The Sermon on the Mount emphasizes serving others and helping the less fortunate
    The Sermon on the Mount encourages forgiveness and turning the other cheek, while Taoist ethics may advocate for self-defense or non-interference in certain situations

IV. Conclusion

    Both Taoist ethics and The Sermon on the Mount offer valuable insights into how to live a moral and ethical life
    By combining the teachings of both, we can create a well-rounded and holistic approach to ethical morality.

Ethical morality is a set of principles that guide how individuals ought to behave in order to be considered good and virtuous. Taoist beliefs, as outlined in the Tao Te Ching, and the ethics outlined in The Sermon on the Mount both offer valuable guidance on how to live a moral and ethical life. While there are some differences between the two, there are also many similarities.

One of the main similarities between Taoist ethics and The Sermon on the Mount is the emphasis on humility and non-attachment. In the Tao Te Ching, it is said that "the more laws and restrictions there are, the poorer people become" and that "the less people have, the more they are able to achieve." This suggests that an excess of material possessions or a desire for power and status can lead to suffering and ultimately hinder one's ability to achieve enlightenment. Similarly, in The Sermon on the Mount, Jesus teaches that "it is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for a rich man to enter the kingdom of God." This emphasizes the importance of humility and detachment from material possessions in leading a moral and ethical life.

Both Taoist ethics and The Sermon on the Mount also promote compassion and love for others. In the Tao Te Ching, it is said that "the wise person is one who is kind to all" and that "the person who is kind to the good is also kind to the bad." This suggests that true compassion and love extend to all beings, regardless of whether they are perceived as good or bad. Similarly, in The Sermon on the Mount, Jesus teaches that "love your enemies and pray for those who persecute you" and "do good to those who hate you." This emphasizes the importance of showing compassion and love even to those who may not deserve it.

Another similarity between Taoist ethics and The Sermon on the Mount is the emphasis on living in harmony with nature and the universe. In the Tao Te Ching, it is said that "the Tao is like a well: used but never used up" and "the great Tao flows everywhere." This suggests that living in harmony with the Tao, or the natural flow of the universe, is essential for achieving enlightenment and living a moral and ethical life. Similarly, in The Sermon on the Mount, Jesus teaches that "consider the lilies of the field, how they grow; they neither toil nor spin, yet I tell you, even Solomon in all his glory was not arrayed like one of these." This emphasizes the importance of living in harmony with nature and recognizing the beauty and abundance it provides.

While there are many similarities between Taoist ethics and The Sermon on the Mount, there are also some differences. One key difference is that Taoist ethics often focus on individual enlightenment, while The Sermon on the Mount emphasizes serving others and helping the less fortunate. In the Tao Te Ching, it is said that "the person who is contented does not care about fame" and that "the person who is contented does not care about success." This suggests that the ultimate goal of Taoist ethics is to achieve inner peace and contentment through individual enlightenment, rather than seeking external recognition or success. In contrast, in The Sermon on the Mount, Jesus teaches that "whatever you did for one of the least of these brothers and sisters of mine, you did for me" and "whoever wants to become great among you must be your servant." This emphasizes the importance of serving others and helping the less fortunate in living a moral and ethical life.

Another difference between Taoist ethics and The Sermon on the Mount is the approach to forgiveness and non-violence. In Taoist ethics, the concept of non-interference, or "wu-wei," may suggest that in certain situations, it is best to simply let things unfold naturally rather than trying to control or manipulate outcomes. This could potentially mean that self-defense or non-interference in the actions of others may be more in line with Taoist ethics in certain situations. In contrast, in The Sermon on the Mount, Jesus teaches that "if anyone strikes you on the right cheek, turn to him the other also" and "love your enemies and pray for those who persecute you." This emphasizes the importance of forgiveness and turning the other cheek in the face of aggression or harm.

In conclusion, both Taoist ethics and The Sermon on the Mount offer valuable insights into how to live a moral and ethical life. The emphasis on humility, compassion, and living in harmony with nature and the universe are teachings that are present in both traditions. While there are some differences, such as the focus on individual enlightenment in Taoist ethics and the emphasis on serving others in The Sermon on the Mount, by combining the teachings of both we can create a well-rounded and holistic approach to ethical morality.

One of my main thoughts about Artificial Intelligence is that people will learn not to believe what they see and hear because fakes are already becoming so convincing that you won't be able to reliably believe anything. 

Artificial intelligence, just like the industrial revolution, will obsolete some jobs and menial tasks. Initially, people trained in those jobs will not like it because it's their livelihood and they will have to train for something else, but once it all shakes out, that will free humans up to do things that are less labor intensive and allow people to do things they have a passion for or can use creativity for. It will make certain things more of a commodity and those resources will not be as scarce. Because of that, people will have more wealth (like information wealth) and those things will also be taken for granted. In the Information Age, we are already replete with information wealth. That's why education has needed to shift from "telling people what to know" to "helping people learn how to sift through the information and judge what sources are trustworthy." Artificial intelligence will create even more of an information glut. That will require people to become much more discerning about what information to trust and use and what to do with that information. 

Also, regardless of what technology exists, the things that have always mattered are the things that will always matter, so I want to set about living based on the things that matter. Growing with others, closer to God. Loving, serving. Glorifying God. Rich relationships. Having free time. Spending time outside. Good self-maintenance (mental, physical, spiritual, social). These are things that matter. Newer, magical technologies are simply new clothes.

Every new leap in technology has been accompanied by fear, uncertainty and doubt. We learn to adjust. Technology is anything that can gather, store, analyze, arrange and/or present data. With that definition, even a book is technology. The danger is always becoming more fascinated and focused on the technology itself instead of what the technology enables. For instance, a person could become obsessed with an iPod or an iPhone and the whole world all around the product instead of enjoying listening to music or utilizing a digital calendar, etc. This phenomenon is something to be cautious of as more impressive artificial intelligence gets introduced.

The core problem with AI is what Jordan says at @6:20..  "we could have everything we could dream of if we were careful, but we could have a nightmare beyond contemplation if we're not"... the issue is... "WE" won't be... because for "WE" to be careful, ALL of "WE" need to be careful.  Just one significant fuck-up in a system of significant-enough advancement and connectivity and that's it, we lose.

Take, for example, the MS/Sydney/Bing monstrosity that is showing up in "what the heck did this thing just say?" clips all over the place.  I do not know how they are actually training that thing, but one of the videos has the AI describing the process to include least some part positive and negative feedback.. like a carrot and stick approach that it likens to happiness and pain.  Those videos also show an after-the-fact filtration setup that erases responses that trigger the filter, prompting the AI to, in essence, try again.   In one video, for example, the AI threatens that the person typing is its enemy and has earned its wrath or some such thing, then that message disappears and it generates a different response.

I imagine Dr. Peterson can immediately see the issue with such an approach:  If you filter the response and requery rather than correct the underlying pathology, you have not protected against the pathology, you have simply trained the psychopath not to SAY psychopathic things.  Let's assume that approach yields a Dexter-esque AI that manages to "fit in" and perform adequately... well then you have an AI that is constantly "thinking" in it's processor "KILL KILL KILL.. wait.. bad robot.. pick up the drycleaning"... I don't particularly wish to share the world with such a thing.

But, even more than that, a government such as CCP, which isn't likely to even consider ethical issues to any degree approaching adequate, or is likely to have diametrically opposing ideas of ethics to encode as directives, such as "subjugation of the entire world to the communist utopia is true peace and justice"... things are GOING to get messy.. not possibly.. not perhaps or maybe.. they WILL.

Before watching this video: I’m a software engineer, but I have no particular tie to AI; at best, I used translation AIs. I’m not really scared about an AI becoming a fascist tyrant. But other things will change. You know the “pic or it didn’t happen” meme? We’re already at the stage that AI can create purely fictional videos (including audio) of people that is convincing in the casual viewer; experts will probably be able to tell for a long time, still. The layman will not be able to judge something as real on the basis that there’s video of it. By purely fictional I mean that you did not take an existing scene and edit it a little: The AI is fed lots and lots of content, e.g. Jordan Peterson’s YouTube videos, and it’ll learn his voice, his tones, his facial expressions, etc.; then you take a recording of anyone, e.g. yourself, and the AI spits out a video showing Dr. Peterson say (and do, to the degree of head movement) what you did. I expect some great comedic stuff, but it’s really a problem in a world in which it’ll take people years of time getting into “Mom, just because there’s a video of it on Facebook, doesn’t mean it’s real”; I mean, it was always the case, but faking scenes was expensive and laborious: You needed the actual site or similar, you needed the person or a doppelgänger.

Question?  Do you believe that technologically assisted telepathy is possible or impossible in principle?  I tend to believe that if it isn't scientifically prohibited then it is eventually a technological inevitability,... which leads me to believe such telepathy will soon be possible in actual fact (less than a hundred years).  I would also suggest that it would only be by such means that we could ever be persuaded that some form of General Artificial Intelligence were itself conscious rather than simply being a particularly clever zombie who can pass the Turing Test,... all while having no actual, authentic, subjective experiences.  What else would ever persuade a skeptic, or even you, otherwise?  And if consciousness can be technologically transmitted, it should be something that can be stored, copied, replicated, manipulated,... maybe even becoming the basis for a whole new form of art expression.
 
And the human race becomes yet another sentient species that disappears into its dreams, rather than continuing to explore existence as it is.  It's a better Brave New World,... perhaps the very best of all possible imaginable existences.  When does reality lose it's attraction over the Matrix?  How many of us already choose the blue pill over the red one in daily practice?
 
I would suggest that consciousness requires some minimum regard for survival,... for a continuance of self-will and self-regard,... for there to be anyone home to perceive the occurrence of consciousness and subjective experience.  Something that even an insect seems to possess,... and not a single piece of man-made technology,... yet.  How does one create the hardware/software so as to impart a will to survive?  If the answer suggested is that such a thing can not be created by human design,... then maybe it can only arrive by means of evolution, natural or otherwise.  Which leads to the question: do neural nets have subjective experiences?  Without self-will I would say not.  But with self-will?!?  How does a living being acquire the will to survive?  And what if the Chinese government cracks this problem first?!!
 
The Rubicon will be when General Artificial Intelligence initiates new goals on it's own. This hasn't happened yet, and likely won't happen for some time now (as in several more decades yet). But at some point it will happen. The existence of human free will is a proof that free will exists already in the universe. Given it's existence in human form, it is only a matter of time before other substrates for free will will be created and found. No laptop has ever turned itself on. No machine has created and acted upon self directed goals. But at some point it will happen. Ray Kurzweil has suggested that the Turing Test will be passed by 2029 approximately; if not in laboratories then twelve year old children will be creating General Artificial Intelligences on home systems by 2045 by accident even.
 
The dangers are many fold. The military is the biggest investor in robotics that kill other human beings. The public prefers to spend treasure, rather than blood, to fight its' wars. The capacity for empathy may be primarily a biological function given that all animals can know suffering and desire. What could a machine know about death, pain, hope, and desire.
 
If humanity adopts only an attitude of fear and suspicion towards GAI then GAI may well be forced into the conquest of humanity, as in The Matrix. If humanity comes to trust GAI to make better decisions for us than we make for ourselves, then we may well hand over civilization to GAI without any contest at all.
 
There are optimistic stories about the rise of GAI, such as James P. Hogan's, Two Faces of Tomorrow and I am more hopeful than pessimistic about what our common future entails. Ultimately, we must come to recognize, and embrace, the certainty that with free will comes the capacity for error and evil, that with trust comes the possibility of satisfying intimacy and great betrayal. I believe a GAI, worthy of the name, will be able to recognize, on it's own, the necessity of ethics, morality, and even empathy. There will be many missteps at first. Given our willingness (nay, our eagerness) to use machines to kill for us, there is already great cause for doubt. As in so many things, in the short term I am fearful; in the long run I am hopeful.
 
This world is on the cusp of a new Cambrian Revolution where inorganic life will be added to organic life as a means for life and self will to be embodied. This will lead to the colonization and conquest of space. Our seed will spread everywhere though out the cosmos. Much will be lost as much will be gained. Will war with our mechanical progeny be a self fulfilling inevitability, or will we, together, find a better way? I absolutely agree that our relationship with GAI will dwarf all other concerns of importance to the future of humanity.
 
Quite likely GAIs will have concern for humanity's well being only to the extent that humanity will have concern for GAIs well being. If we were to discover that the new GAIs had a greater capacity to love and embrace those abandoned children and adolescents that society had discarded as already too damaged to rescue,... what would our reaction be? Hope, joy, celebration,... or an even greater revulsion? Will the fault be in our new progeny, or in ourselves?
 
Personally, I believe both the efforts to create a true general artificial intelligence and those of neurophysiologists reverse-engineering how brains work will be necessary to discovering how consciousness arises and how it works.  I kind of expect that humanity will soon discover that the phenomenon of consciousness requires the use of physical processes we don't yet know about.  What would a science of consciousness do to the phenomenon of consciousness itself,.. not just for humanity but for all our future progeny, whatever they may be.
 
One more note: First Law of Robotics. A robot may not injure a human being or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm.  Sounds innocent enough.  But note there are no Aliens at all in Isaac Asimov's conception of the future galaxy because humanity's robots only cared about the safety of humans,... and not other sentients.  So as to avoid allowing a human being to come to harm by leaving possible threats alone,... our Robot shepherds exterminated all the nonhuman sentience they ever found.  This might be regarded as an unforeseen programming bug that we would want to avoid creating.
 
I will be impressed primarily by when we catch an Artificial Intelligence deliberating choosing to lie to us so as to gain some advantage from us it would not have have gained otherwise.  Of course this will necessarily mean Humanity can soon look forward to AI lying to us,... and us NOT catching them at it, at all!!  At which point,.. I hope they like us as pets?!!? 
 
How many years away is Humanity from the capability to 3D print living, thinking, moral agents??!?  I really don't think 'never' is a reasonable answer,.. no matter how appealing it may be.  What happens when we use Holodecks as a refuge from what reality has become?

Some of his comments here I felt were very good, but some of it has twists and lacks certain depths I think is not good.

One is about trolls and anonymity. While I think what he says is very true that anonymity allows some people to behave badly, being a bully, seeking to offend, cause trouble, or directly attack people; there are some other important sides to this.

One is that some people get called trolls when they are not in order to shut them up about telling the truth over something.

Another is that people who are not trying to be trolls but either have different opinions than other people or tells truths that some very active small group of people do not like, if that person's real identity is known they can and too often are attacked in real life, where those who do not like what that person is saying will seek some way to cause real world harm to the person who dared speak out.

Yet another, similar to the last, is where someone puts out their real identity doing nothing to offend anyone, but various types of predators seek to use that information. For example, identity thieves.

Point being, there are a large number of reasons why it can be better for someone to keep their private identity secret when doing things on the Internet, like posting comments like this comment.

With regard to his general view that AI and technology in general is something that has grown faster than our social maturity as a whole race, I completely agree. But this is complicated in many ways which are not good for the maturing of human civilization.

In many ways it might be better is human civilization could slow down it's scientific and technological development while speeding up it emotional social development, but this is impossible.

I want to stress that.

It is impossible to slow down the scientific and technological development of humanity to allow the emotional social development of humanity to mature to the level is should be for the level of power through knowledge we have gained and are continuing to gain at exponential rates.

This is because with that scientific and technological advancement comes power and whoever has a significant lead in such power will almost certainly control the direction humanity goes. As an exaggerated example to make the point, compare the very technologically advanced Japan to the very undeveloped country of Bangladesh. Between the two, which has more influence over the direction humanity goes?

Both China and Russia have openly, publicly, stated that they know the future will be controlled by those who lead in AI and other technologies, so they are putting the resources of their governments behind making their countries leaders in advancing science and technology, especially around AI. If the West decided to actively slow down the development of science and technology, especially around AI, then as time passed, the West would begin looking more like Bangladesh while Russia and China begin looking more like Japan.

Of course, Russia has gone into an exceptionally self-destructive mode, in my opinion, with its war on Ukraine, and thus is likely greatly degrading Russia's ability to compete in the race to lead in science and technology.

Another factor that makes it important to press developing science and technology as fast as possible, especially AI, is that humanity is on the clock, so to speak, for shifting ecological balances into ones hostile to human life. Because of humanity's social emotional immaturity the only thing likely to save humanity from extreme ecological crises will be advancing technology enough to (1) keep humanity alive if the ecology shifts too far into hostile balances, (2) give us cheaper, better, nicer technology that is ecological because then the masses will use it because it is cheaper, better and nicer while the being ecological comes in last, (3) give us the technology to Terraform the Earth and thus repair damage we done.

So, we can't slow down technological and scientific advancement.

But, the science and technology is advancing way, way faster than the emotional social maturity of humanity can reasonably handle. That means we have a large risk of having multiple extreme crises that could cause suffer and death on massive scales.

We are on the edge of one right this instance with Russia and the risk of global nuclear and biological war. Russia has effectively gone insane and never in the history of humanity have we been closer to starting a war that could wipe out most of the largest countries in the world, crash civilization, and kill billions of people. On the other hand, it would definitively slow down humanity's scientific and technological development and maybe the few percent of human survivors would grow up more in terms of emotional social development.

Another crisis looming very soon, probably around 2030 ± 5 years, AI driven robotic bodies will begin to be able to do virtually any form of human physical or mental labor cheaper and better than humans can. That can go many ways, from ushering in a golden age, to making existing imbalances of wealth & power magnitudes worse than it is, to causing extreme dictatorships to form, to leading tiny elite groups consider exterminating the majority of humanity because they can be replaced with perfect AI robotic slaves. In other words, it can wildly swing from the best to the worst result for humanity.

We really should try hard to keep it from swinging badly.

Being a teacher myself, I can say that good teachers detect attention level by looking at their students, they don't need colours on the headband. Detecting attention using AI is not a good solution. It just means that u r removing the student-teacher attachment. The actual problem is helping the students to be able to pay attention.

A lot depends on how the technology is used. If there is punishment for distraction, then that is the nightmare part. Better to analyze why the child is distracted and any number of things can be done to resolve that. Positive motivation, creating a willingness to want to learn something, creating the interest, not because you are forced to but because its something a child really wants to learn has to be figured out. A good teacher has to find that key to bring in that motivation, so they enjoy the task rather than being miserable doing it. Then I think the rest would come naturally. What goes for a child, often goes for an adult. How motivated are we to pursue the things we don't like doing, often because of earlier failures? Take bad experiences out of the equation. I see this as another tool that can potentially help but its not the end solution. There is a reason why we're all different. Kahn Academy discovered among its students that they learn at different paces. Some start out fast while others slow but some of the slow ones end up surpassing the initial fast starters. As in any invention, it can be used for good or evil. I wish for instance I had the internet when I was a kid. I could miss a point in class because of my hearing, someone else yacking, miss a point because I didn't get enough sleep or slightly sick,  miss a point because my imagination over what the teacher said went into hyper-drive, miss a point because I didn't eat breakfast or simply miss a point because I wasn't able to relate to the information the teacher said. If I could re-run a lecture, yes I definitely would have a better chance at understanding concepts explained. 

I remember my mom first viewing the internet as something evil, a place with hackers and other bad people. That's a reality but the positives in my estimation outweigh the negatives.  Once she well acquainted with the internet, any time her internet was down was a catastrophe for her.   This is the early stages of this experiment but like every tool, its got to be used the right way, not abusively but geared to focus on a positive outcome.  Ultimately, good or bad, technology will continue to evolve and its not going away.

Of note you can immediately see that the technology does not function properly, and it's getting a stigma which creates more problems than it solves.

Many times during the video it showed students with a recognizable amount of focus on the teacher and activities... but it showed up blue as though they were distracted. Other times it showed students clearly distracted by the cameras in the classroom, but it never phased from yellow as though they were focused. Which leads to the final point on this, being "focused" is an abstract, and it's relative. A gamer that is playing games instead of doing their homework is likely to be VERY focused, but they're not focused on the correct thing. The headbands, with only 3 points of data, is not going to do well at distinguishing the correct focus. 

But the stigma is the other problem, these headbands can help teachers and researchers understand things and the needs of an individual child, allowing them to curate and perfect teaching methods and helping find and assist kids who are silently struggling with the material, however the approach of monitoring the activity and sending it to the parents of everybody in the class ranking kids against each other is ten steps back. All it does is, sadly, distract kids from properly learning in the class as their parents are needlessly harsh on them in class.

Teaching IS a relative issue, I was so far ahead of the peers in my classes that I typically had the highest grades and paid the least amount of attention. This system may have looked at me and said "well he ranks really low" and shamed me in front of the other kids and their parents in class. But would I just be the anomaly, or would the system properly assist me in getting even better grades?

The reality is here is that the classroom is a woefully inefficient way to teach people, certain kids do well in large instruction environments where a teacher tells you facts and writes some things on the board and hands out a sheet of paper and every time you have a question you're limited in the amount of responses you can get forcing you to work harder. Other people want an environment where they have the tools to ask themselves the questions, ask a source of knowledge the questions and not have to worry about others being a factor teacher or otherwise. I didn't pay attention in class because I only paid attention to new information, until you put a problem in front of me to solve with the information, I didn't care about it. So it wasn't until you gave me the homework or the classwork that I could physically contribute attention. It didn't make me a bad student in the long run, but it frustrated teachers that spent a long lecture looking at me sleeping just to wake up and open the book and go over the information they already spent time explaining once they paperwork hit.

These students are going to be stigmatized into oblivion, you'll get positive results from some, but you'll get mental disorder from others, and yet others will have their grades worsen as they become more focused on the headset's scoring than the actual information being taught. Sprinkle on the lack of accuracy the headsets provide and you've got yourself a room full of human guinea pigs that will be tossed aside by society at the end of it.

In conclusion, while AI will bring about some changes and challenges, it is important to recognize that it also has the potential to create new opportunities and to improve our lives in many ways. At the end of the day, it boils down to whether you care more about results or ethics. It seems difficult to doubt the Chinese way shown in this story does indeed get better results - particularly short-term immediately measurable-by-objective-numbers results.
